		   <table class="mform"  border="0" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="0" width="100%">
		   <tr><td class="headerrow" colspan="2" class="mform" valign="top">How I went from lvl 1 - 45 in 16days playing time<br clear=all>
		   <span class="sm">Posted @ Thu, Apr 5th 3:52 AM 2001 </span><span id="notbold">| <span class=sm>IP: Logged</span> | <a href="/db/classes.html?class=1&mid=98645716485590&post=1"><a class=sm href="/db/classes.html?class=1&mid=98645716485590&num=3&page=&post=1&replyto=98645716485590"><img src=/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=11 width=17> Reply to this</a></a>   <a name=98645716485590></a></small></td></tr>
		   <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id=>Anonymous</span></a><b><span id=></span></b>
		   <br><nobr><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default [2.00]</nobr><br><br><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p>This post is for all you newbs that have no idea where to lvl.&nbsp;&nbsp;Don't sweet it, I will tell you exactly where to fight.  This is exactly what I did, and it resulted in me lvling from 1 - 44 in 18days.  From lvl 1 - 5, fight in the zone that your home town is connected to.  All newbies start off in newbie areas, so take advantage of it.  From lvl 5 - 9, fight in South Ro.  Camp near the zone to Oasis Marr.  Kill spiders and mummies and such.  Pull them to the zone so that if you get in trouble, you can just turn and zone.  Next, from lvl 9 - 12 fight in east commons.  The area you should camp is the area right near the zone to Kithicor Woods.  At this point, you can kill young kodiaks, giant spiders, dartweed snakes and so on.  At lvl 12, start grouping.  Go to oasis marr and fight there from lvl 12 - 20.  Oasis Marr is by far the best area to fight at this lvl, and is extremely populated, which makes it very safe.  At lvl 20, go South Karana and fight Aviaks at the Aviak bird house.  It's easy to find a group there, and the experience is very good.  Once you hit lvl 25, move to an Outside Paw group, and fight there up to 28 or so.  At 28, go inside Paw and fight there up to 33.  Once you hit 33, go to the Overthere and get a group there. Fight there up to 40.  Once you hit 40, go to the Dreadlands.  I've been at the Dreadlands since 40.  <br><br>This is the best way to get exp fast.  My friend is a lvl 41 warrior with over 30 days playing time.  He was amazed with the speed at which I was able to lvl.  I hope you found this advice to be helpful.<br><br>later</p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width="100%"><tr><td id=fs8></td><td align=right id=fs8 >3 Replies</td></tr></table></td></tr></table><tr><td>
		   <table class="mform2"  border="0" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="0" width="100%">
		   <tr><td class="headerrow" colspan="2" class="mform2" valign="top">
		   <span class="sm">Posted @ Sat, Apr 7th 12:06 AM 2001 </span><span id="notbold">| <span class=sm>IP: Logged</span> | <a class=sm href="/db/classes.html?class=1&mid=98645716485590&num=3&page=&post=1&replyto=98661637727086"><img src=/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=11 width=17> Reply to this</a></a>   <a name=98661637727086></a></small></td></tr>
		   <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform2><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id=>Anonymous</span></a><b><span id=></span></b>
		   <br><nobr><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default [2.00]</nobr><br><br><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform2" width="100%"><p>I would like to take this chance to address an issue that has been bothering me since I started playing this game, as well as give some (read all) players a different sense of perspective. A lot of conversation revolves around leveling up, getting items, getting exp, etc. What I rarely hear about is playing the actual game. Hey, guys (and gals), guess what? This is not Diablo, or Baldur's Gate, or any of the other dozens of such games. You don't play this game to win, you play it to enjoy the experience. Don't treat your character as a point-gathering machine, an item-acquisition vehicle. You are robbing yourself of a truly wonderful experience - a chance to enter a different world, where you get to slay (and be slain by, though not YOU personally, of course :) dragons and clear out kobold camps. If you just leave that goblin alone for a second, look up into the sky (provided it's daytime, of course), and comment outloud something like "&lt;your name&gt; takes a breath of fresh air, preparing himself mentally for battle," you just might get something out of it that's more meaningful than the few points of experience. The goblin will still be there, but it will be YOU personally that defeated it, not your character. EverQuest can be a chore, where you are always in a rush to get better armour, more spells, and advance another level, or it can be something amazing, an alternate reality, a world away from this one. But the choice is, ultimately, yours. </p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform2"><table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width="100%"><tr><td id=fs8></td><td align=right id=fs8 >0 Replies</td></tr></table></td></tr></table><tr><td>
		   <table class="mform"  border="0" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="0" width="100%">
