		   <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id=>Anonymous</span></a><b><span id=></span></b>
		   <br><nobr><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default [2.00]</nobr><br><br><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p>I would like to take this chance to address an issue that has been bothering me since I started playing this game, as well as give some (read all) players a different sense of perspective. A lot of conversation revolves around leveling up, getting items, getting exp, etc. What I rarely hear about is playing the actual game. Hey, guys (and gals), guess what? This is not Diablo, or Baldur's Gate, or any of the other dozens of such games. You don't play this game to win, you play it to enjoy the experience. Don't treat your character as a point-gathering machine, an item-acquisition vehicle. You are robbing yourself of a truly wonderful experience - a chance to enter a different world, where you get to slay (and be slain by, though not YOU personally, of course :) dragons and clear out kobold camps. If you just leave that goblin alone for a second, look up into the sky (provided it's daytime, of course), and comment outloud something like "&lt;your name&gt; takes a breath of fresh air, preparing himself mentally for battle," you just might get something out of it that's more meaningful than the few points of experience. The goblin will still be there, but it will be YOU personally that defeated it, not your character. EverQuest can be a chore, where you are always in a rush to get better armour, more spells, and advance another level, or it can be something amazing, an alternate reality, a world away from this one. But the choice is, ultimately, yours. </p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width="100%"><tr><td id=fs8></td><td align=right id=fs8 >0 Replies</td></tr></table></td></tr></table><tr><td>
